{{commonscat|Naka-hikawa-jinja (Yamaguchi, Tokorozawa)|Naka-Hikawa Shrine (Yamaguchi, Tokorozawa)}}
'''Naka-Hikawa Shrine''' (なかひかわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} of {{ill|lt=Hikawa faith|Q11549596|qid=Q11549596|1=Hikawa shinkō}} in {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi (Tokorozawa)|Q11466558|qid=Q11466558|lt=Yamaguchi|1=Yamaguchi}}, {{ill|lt=Tokorozawa|Q165857|qid=Q165857|1=Tokorozawa, Saitama}}, {{ill|lt=Saitama Prefecture|Q128186|qid=Q128186|1=Saitama Prefecture}}. It was the general guardian of 92 villages in former {{ill|lt=Iruma District|Q1153801|qid=Q1153801|1=Iruma District, Saitama}} and {{ill|lt=Tama District|Q11430789|qid=Q11430789|1=Tama district}}, and was a former {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}.

=== Overview ===
* It is a candidate shrine for Naka-Hikawa-sha, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}. Like Ōmiya {{ill|lt=Hikawa Shrine|Q703633|qid=Q703633|1=Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)}}, it enshrines three deities: {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, {{ill|qid=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime|Q505469|qid=Q505469|qid=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime-no-Mikoto|1=Kushinadahime}}, and {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}.
* "Naka" in Naka-Hikawa is explained as: midway between Ōmiya Hikawa Shrine and {{ill|lt=Oku-Hikawa Shrine|Q11445942|qid=Q11445942|1=Oku-Hikawa Shrine}} ({{ill|lt=Okutama|Q598626|qid=Q598626|1=Okutama, Tokyo}}, {{ill|lt=Nishitama District|Q1048689|qid=Q1048689|1=Nishitama District}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|qid=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}), or midway between Ōmiya Hikawa Shrine and the {{ill|lt=provincial capital|Q1629088|qid=Q1629088|1=Kokufu}} of {{ill|lt=Musashi Province|Q907398|qid=Q907398|1=Musashi Province}} ({{ill|lt=Fuchū, Tokyo|Q208818|qid=Q208818|lt=Fuchū|1=Fuchū, Tokyo}}).
* Locally it has long been called "Hikawa-sama."

=== History ===
* Traditionally founded in the reign of Emperor Sujin.
* In late {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi Ietsugu|Q11466765|qid=Q11466765|1=Yamaguchi Ietsugu}} built shrine buildings. They later burned in warfare, but in the {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} era (1573-1593), {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi Takatada|Q11467543|qid=Q11467543|1=Yamaguchi Takatada}} restored it together with {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi Castle (Musashi)|Q11466729|qid=Q11466729|lt=Yamaguchi Castle|1=Yamaguchi Castle}}.
* In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 20 ({{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|qid=Q5240|1=1945}}), Brigadier General Ken R. Dyke, first director of GHQ/CIE, inspected this shrine's festival.

===Shrine buildings / precinct===
*Honden: {{ill|lt=taisha-zukuri|Q387874|qid=Q387874|1=Taisha-zukuri}}, built in 1927.
*Shichisha Shrine: moved into the precincts from an area scheduled to be submerged by {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi Reservoir|Q11467481|qid=Q11467481|1=Yamaguchi Reservoir}}.

===Festivals===
*Spring grand festival is on the first Sunday of April; autumn grand festival is on Sports Day in October.

===Location / transportation===
*Saitama Prefecture, Tokorozawa, Yamaguchi 1849
**15 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Shimo-Yamaguchi Station|Q7496941|qid=Q7496941|1=Shimo-Yamaguchi Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Seibu Sayama Line|Q1965549|qid=Q1965549|1=Seibu Sayama Line}}

